body:
The module hierarchy files that `HWExportModuleHierarchy` produce are incorrect if any instances are renamed. This is stemming from the pass directly emitting a file using the instance name instead of the VerilogName or, even better, a Verbatim.

Here is a minimal example compiling with `firtool Foo.fir -export-module-hierarchy -split-verilog -o Foo`:

```
circuit Foo: %[[
  {
    "class": "sifive.enterprise.firrtl.ModuleHierarchyAnnotation",
    "filename": "dut_hier.json"
  },
  {
    "class": "sifive.enterprise.firrtl.TestHarnessHierarchyAnnotation",
    "filename": "tb_hier.json"
  },
  {
    "class": "sifive.enterprise.firrtl.MarkDUTAnnotation",
    "target": "~Foo|Bar"
  },
  {
    "class": "firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation",
    "target": "~Foo|Baz>a"
  },
  {
    "class": "chisel3.util.experimental.ForceNameAnnotation",
    "target": "~Foo|Foo>bar",
    "name": "HELLO_bar"
  },
  {
    "class": "chisel3.util.experimental.ForceNameAnnotation",
    "target": "~Foo|Bar>baz",
    "name": "WORLD_baz"
  }
]]
  module Baz:
    wire a: UInt<1>
    a is invalid
  module Bar:
    inst baz of Baz
  module Foo:
    inst bar of Bar
```

This produces:

```json
{
  "instance_name": "Bar",
  "module_name": "Bar",
  "instances": [
    {
      "instance_name": "baz",
      "module_name": "Baz",
      "instances": []
    }
  ]
}
```

And:

```json
{
  "instance_name": "Foo",
  "module_name": "Foo",
  "instances": [
    {
      "instance_name": "bar",
      "module_name": "Bar",
      "instances": [
        {
          "instance_name": "baz",
          "module_name": "Baz",
          "instances": []
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

The instance names are incorrect and should be `HELLO_bar` and `WORLD_baz`.

Note: there are two related issues:

1. That pass does not use an `sv.verbatim` and instead directly writes files. This should be changed to use a verbatim.
2. That pass interprets the default output directory (`-`) literally and will create this directory if you don't run with `-split-verilog -o=file`. This should also be changed to dump the files out in the current directory.
